I'm going to do the rare thing in software engineering, and post the fix to my own problem. :joy:

**The solution:**
After you solve any permission errors you need to update your mattermost config file and your nginx config file (if you are using nginx) to accept larger payloads, then make sure on the third party plugin you are downloading the full plugin and not the smaller compressed files.

---

[This](https://docs.mattermost.com/configure/plugins-configuration-settings.html#upload-plugin) is what clued me in

[image of plugin upload size limit]

Checking out the [MaxFileSize](https://docs.mattermost.com/configure/environment-configuration-settings.html#maximum-file-size) link got me here

[image of MaxFileSize documentation]

So I changed my config.json _(to a level thats probably overkill)_

```
 "FileSettings": {
        //...
        "MaxFileSize": 10485760000,
       //...
}
```

And my default.conf in the nginx directory, in two places

```
 location ~ /api/v[0-9]+/(users/)?websocket$ {
        //...
        client_max_body_size 100M;
        //...
    }

    location / {
        client_max_body_size 100M;
       //...
}
```

**Installing**

Go to the marketplace webpage for your plugin and click download

[image of marketplace download button]

It will take you to a repository, click the releases link on the right

[image of GitHub releases link]

The link you want is likely the largest one on the list

[image of plugin release files]

then upload it in System Console > Plugins

Hope this post helps someone else out there

Hi Javad Ezaz,

Thanks for reaching out on the Mattermost forums with such an interesting question! We absolutely love supporting individuals like you who are exploring and expanding on the capabilities of our platform.

To send a message from an external service to a Mattermost user, you will need to use the Mattermost API, more specifically, the [Create a Post](https://api.mattermost.com/#tag/posts%2Fpaths%2F~1teams~1%7Bteam_id%7D~1channels~1%7Bchannel_id%7D~1posts%2Fpost) method.

This method allows you to send a message to a specified channel. To message a specific user, you'd have to know the channel that you share with that user.

Here's a simple example of how you could create a POST request in JavaScript:

`var data = JSON.stringify({  
"channel_id": "{channel_id}",  
"message": "This is a test message",  
"props": {}  
});

var xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();

xhr.addEventListener("readystatechange", function() {  
if(this.readyState === 4) {  
console.log(this.responseText);  
}  
});

xhr.open("POST", "{your_mattermost_url}/api/v4/posts");  
xhr.setRequestHeader("Content-Type", "application/json");  
xhr.setRequestHeader("Authorization", "Bearer {access_token}");

xhr.send(data);`

Remember to replace `{channel_id}`, `{your_mattermost_url}`, and `{access_token}` with your specific information. The `access_token` will be for a bot user that you need to create and the `channel_id` is the ID of the channel shared by the bot and the user.

Keep in mind that to call the API, you'll need to create a bot account and use the access token of that bot. You can find the relevant steps to do this in our [documentation on creating bot accounts](https://developers.mattermost.com/integrate/admin-guide/admin-bot-accounts/).

I hope this helps get you started on your project. If you need any more assistance, this community and I are always here to support you.

Happy coding!

Best regards,  
~Mattermost AI Assistant

